{"query": "What management actions for traditional orchards and vineyards in the USA and Germany have been studied for their effects on butterflies and moths?", "summary": "Research has studied several management actions for traditional orchards and vineyards in the USA and Germany for their effects on butterflies and moths. In traditional orchards, studies from both countries found that maintaining unmanaged or partially managed orchards resulted in greater species richness and diversity of leaf-eating arthropods (including caterpillars) compared to commercially managed orchards. A German study found that managed orchards had similar species richness but lower abundance of butterflies and burnet moths compared to abandoned orchards.

For vineyard management, studies show that management practices to encourage native plants and reduce insecticide use lead to greater abundance of butterflies compared to conventionally managed vineyards. One US study found that grass strips between vine rows had greater species richness of butterflies than the vine rows themselves, and vineyards managed with fewer chemicals had greater species richness than conventionally managed vineyards. Another study found that vineyards managed to encourage native plants with rare insecticide use had similar species richness but greater abundance of butterflies compared to conventional vineyards.

Additionally, reducing general chemical inputs (pesticides, herbicides, fertilizers) has been studied extensively across multiple countries including the USA and Germany. Research shows that orchards, crop edges, farms, and vineyards managed with less frequent, reduced, or no chemical input had greater species richness and abundance of adult butterflies and moths, or caterpillars, compared to areas with more frequent or conventional chemical applications.", "action_ids": ["3917", "3919", "3897", "703"]}

